  "prompt": "At what point do a sperm cell and an egg become a boy or a girl?",
  "response": "The determination of a fetus's sex occurs at the moment of fertilization, when a sperm cell successfully fertilizes an egg cell. Sex is determined by the chromosomes contributed by the sperm cell. Human eggs contain one X chromosome, while sperm cells can contain either an X or a Y chromosome. If a sperm cell with an X chromosome fertilizes the egg, the resulting combination will be XX, which typically develops into a female. If a sperm cell with a Y chromosome fertilizes the egg, the resulting combination will be XY, which typically develops into a male.\n\nHowever, the phenotypic differentiation into male or female (physical characteristics) happens later during fetal development, influenced primarily by the presence of certain hormones and other factors. This includes the development of sex-specific organs and secondary sexual characteristics.",
